A better approach would be to prove `⨆ i, (a_i + b_i) ≤ (⨆ i, a_i) + (⨆ i, b_i)` because for any `i`, `a_i + b_i ≤ (⨆ i, a_i) + (⨆ i, b_i)`. Since this holds for all `i`, we take the supremum of the left-hand side. 

This is easier to formalize because `a_i ≤ (⨆ i, a_i)` and `b_i ≤ (⨆ i, b_i)` implies `a_i + b_i ≤ (⨆ i, a_i) + (⨆ i, b_i)` for each `i`, so their supremum is bounded by `(⨆ i, a_i) + (⨆ i, b_i)`. 

Here is how it should work:
```lean
have h₁ : ⨆ i : ι, (eLpNorm (X i) 2 P + eLpNorm (Y i) 2 P) ≤ (⨆ i : ι, eLpNorm (X i) 2 P) + (⨆ i : ι, eLpNorm (Y i) 2 P) := by
  -- For any i, a_i + b_i ≤ (sup_i a_i) + (sup_i b_i)
  refine le_trans (iSup_le fun i ↦ le_add (le_iSup (fun i ↦ eLpNorm (X i) 2 P) i) (le_iSup (fun i ↦ eLpNorm (Y i) 2 P) i)) _
  -- The sum of the suprema is greater than or equal to the supremum of the sum?
  <;> simp [add_comm]
  <;> try simp_all [add_assoc]
  <;> try norm_num
```

But this is not actually correct, because for each `i`, we have `a_i ≤ (⨆ i, a_i)` and `b_i ≤ (⨆ i, b_i)`, so `a_i + b_i ≤ (⨆ i, a_i) + (⨆ i, b_i)`, but the supremum of the LHS (`iSup`) over `i` of `a_i + b_i` is bounded by `(⨆ i, a_i) + (⨆ i, b_i)`, because the RHS does not depend on `i`. 

The `iSup_le` lemma does exactly that: if for every `i`, `a_i ≤ b`, then `⨆ i, a_i ≤ b`. Here, for every `i`, `a_i + b_i ≤ (⨆ i, a_i) + (⨆ i, b_i)` (which does not depend on `i`), so `⨆ i, (a_i + b_i) ≤ (⨆ i, a_i) + (⨆ i, b_i)`.

This is much simpler than the previous approach with `ciSup_add_le` (which is not actually needed here).

